---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
---

<Base title="Evidence-Based Treatments">
  <article class="container page-section">
    <h1>Treatment Approaches</h1>

    <p style="font-size: 1.1rem; color: var(--text-muted); max-width: 650px;">
      The treatment landscape for neuroplastic pain has transformed dramatically. Here are the
      evidence-based approaches — what they are, how they work, and what the research shows.
    </p>

    <div class="card" style="margin: 1.5rem 0; background: var(--teal-light);">
      <p style="margin: 0; line-height: 1.7;">
        <strong>Core principle:</strong> All effective treatments for neuroplastic pain share one
        goal — <strong>teaching the brain that the pain signal is a false alarm</strong>. They
        differ in method but converge on the same mechanism: reducing the threat value of pain
        sensations so the brain stops generating them.
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- PRT -->
    <section style="margin: 2.5rem 0;">
      <div style="display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 0.75rem; margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
        <div style="background: var(--teal); color: white; border-radius: 50%; width: 40px; height: 40px; display: flex; align-items: center; justify-content: center; font-weight: 700; font-size: 1.2rem;">1</div>
        <h2 style="margin: 0; border: none;">Pain Reprocessing Therapy (PRT)</h2>
      </div>
      <p style="color: var(--text-muted); font-size: 0.9rem; margin-bottom: 1rem;">
        Developed by Alan Gordon, LCSW — systematic brain retraining protocol
      </p>

      <p>
        PRT is a system of psychological techniques that retrains the brain to interpret signals
        from the body correctly, breaking the chronic pain cycle. It is the most rigorously studied
        neuroplastic pain treatment, validated in a landmark <em>JAMA Psychiatry</em> trial.
      </p>

      <div class="card" style="margin: 1rem 0; border-left: 4px solid var(--teal);">
        <h3 style="margin-top: 0; font-size: 1rem;">The five components of PRT</h3>
        <ol style="margin-bottom: 0; line-height: 1.8;">
          <li><strong>Education</strong> — learning why pain persists due to brain mechanisms, not tissue damage. Understanding that the pain is real but that it can be reversed.</li>
          <li><strong>Gathering personalized evidence</strong> — identifying evidence in your own life that your pain is neuroplastic (the checklist). Building conviction.</li>
          <li><strong>Somatic tracking</strong> — the core technique: attending to pain sensations with curiosity and safety (not fear), observing without reacting, gradually retraining the brain's threat response.</li>
          <li><strong>Addressing emotional threats</strong> — processing the underlying emotions (stress, anger, grief, trauma) that the pain may be protecting you from.</li>
          <li><strong>Gravitating to positive feelings</strong> — actively cultivating joy, connection, and safety to counterbalance the threat-dominant state.</li>
        </ol>
      </div>

      <div class="card" style="background: #F0FDFA; border-color: var(--teal);">
        <h3 style="margin-top: 0; font-size: 1rem;">The evidence</h3>
        <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 0.95rem;">
          <strong>JAMA Psychiatry (2021):</strong> 66% pain-free or nearly pain-free after 8 sessions
          over 4 weeks. 98% improved. Results maintained at 1-year and 5-year follow-ups.
          <a href="https://jamanetwork.com/journals/jamapsychiatry/fullarticle/2784694" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Read the full study →</a>
        </p>
      </div>

      <p>
        <a href="/protocols/prt" style="font-weight: 600;">Full PRT protocol page →</a> with
        somatic tracking instructions and the step-by-step process.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- EAET -->
    <section style="margin: 2.5rem 0;">
      <div style="display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 0.75rem; margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
        <div style="background: var(--teal); color: white; border-radius: 50%; width: 40px; height: 40px; display: flex; align-items: center; justify-content: center; font-weight: 700; font-size: 1.2rem;">2</div>
        <h2 style="margin: 0; border: none;">Emotional Awareness and Expression Therapy (EAET)</h2>
      </div>
      <p style="color: var(--text-muted); font-size: 0.9rem; margin-bottom: 1rem;">
        Developed by Mark Lumley, PhD and Howard Schubiner, MD
      </p>

      <p>
        EAET targets the emotional roots of neuroplastic pain. The premise: when emotions are
        suppressed (especially anger, grief, and fear), the nervous system may express them
        through physical symptoms. EAET helps patients:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>Identify avoided or suppressed emotions — particularly anger about past hurts</li>
        <li>Express these emotions directly — in writing, verbally, or through experiential exercises</li>
        <li>Process childhood adversity, relationship conflicts, and trauma in a structured way</li>
        <li>Reduce the internal pressure that maintains central sensitization</li>
      </ul>

      <p>
        <strong>Evidence:</strong> EAET outperformed CBT for fibromyalgia (Lumley & Schubiner, PAIN 2017)
        and for older veterans with chronic pain (Yarns et al., Pain Medicine 2020). A 2023 Swedish
        trial found that internet-delivered EAET was effective for somatic symptom disorder.
      </p>

      <p>
        EAET is especially indicated when there is a clear history of trauma, childhood adversity,
        or long-suppressed emotional conflict — and when the patient feels ready to explore
        these connections.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- Schubiner's Method -->
    <section style="margin: 2.5rem 0;">
      <div style="display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 0.75rem; margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
        <div style="background: var(--teal); color: white; border-radius: 50%; width: 40px; height: 40px; display: flex; align-items: center; justify-content: center; font-weight: 700; font-size: 1.2rem;">3</div>
        <h2 style="margin: 0; border: none;">Schubiner's Unlearn Your Pain Program</h2>
      </div>
      <p style="color: var(--text-muted); font-size: 0.9rem; margin-bottom: 1rem;">
        Developed by Howard Schubiner, MD — workbook-based self-directed program
      </p>

      <p>
        Schubiner's approach integrates neuroscience education with emotional processing and practical
        techniques. The program (available as a workbook and online course) guides patients through
        three phases: <strong>Education, Evidence, and Experience</strong>.
      </p>
      <p>
        A key insight of Schubiner's method: most people can recover without extensive psychotherapy
        or revisiting trauma in detail. Understanding the mechanism and applying simple techniques
        with commitment is often sufficient. The brain needs to unlearn the pain pattern — not
        necessarily analyze its origins.
      </p>
      <p>
        <a href="/protocols/schubiner" style="font-weight: 600;">Full Schubiner protocol page →</a>
        with the three-phase approach and specific techniques.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- Sarno's approach -->
    <section style="margin: 2.5rem 0;">
      <div style="display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 0.75rem; margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
        <div style="background: var(--teal); color: white; border-radius: 50%; width: 40px; height: 40px; display: flex; align-items: center; justify-content: center; font-weight: 700; font-size: 1.2rem;">4</div>
        <h2 style="margin: 0; border: none;">Sarno's TMS Approach (the foundation)</h2>
      </div>
      <p style="color: var(--text-muted); font-size: 0.9rem; margin-bottom: 1rem;">
        Developed by the late John E. Sarno, MD — the originator of mind-body pain theory
      </p>

      <p>
        Sarno observed that most chronic pain patients shared certain personality characteristics:
        perfectionism, people-pleasing, and a tendency to internalize stress. He proposed that the
        brain creates physical pain as a distraction from unbearable emotions — particularly rage
        that the conscious mind won't acknowledge.
      </p>
      <p>
        His treatment was elegantly simple: patients attended a lecture explaining TMS, read his
        book (typically <em>Healing Back Pain</em>), and were instructed to think psychologically
        when pain appeared — to recognize it as a brain-generated distraction rather than a
        structural problem. No psychotherapy, no exercises, no drugs. Thousands recovered.
      </p>
      <p>
        While modern approaches (PRT, EAET) have refined and systematized Sarno's insights with
        rigorous clinical trials, his foundational contribution cannot be overstated. He was
        decades ahead of the neuroscience.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- Other effective approaches -->
    <h2>Other evidence-supported approaches</h2>

    <div style="display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
      <div class="card" style="border-left: 4px solid var(--teal);">
        <h3 style="margin-top: 0; font-size: 1rem;">Pain Neuroscience Education (PNE)</h3>
        <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 0.9rem;">Simply learning about central sensitization and
        neuroplastic pain reduces pain, fear, and disability. Reading this page is already
        therapeutic. Multiple RCTs confirm PNE as an effective standalone intervention.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="card" style="border-left: 4px solid var(--teal);">
        <h3 style="margin-top: 0; font-size: 1rem;">Graded Exposure / Graded Motor Imagery</h3>
        <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 0.9rem;">Gradually and safely re-introducing feared movements
        and sensations. Start with imagining the movement, progress to visualization, then tiny
        physical movements — always staying within your "window of tolerance" while expanding it.
        Used extensively for CRPS and phantom limb pain, effective for all centrally-driven pain.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="card" style="border-left: 4px solid var(--teal);">
        <h3 style="margin-top: 0; font-size: 1rem;">Internal Family Systems (IFS) for Pain</h3>
        <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 0.9rem;">IFS conceives of the mind as composed of "parts" —
        some of which may generate pain to protect vulnerable exiled emotions. By dialoguing with
        pain-generating parts with compassion, patients often experience rapid shifts. Schubiner and
        IFS founder Richard Schwartz co-authored an article on this approach for the Psychotherapy
        Networker.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="card" style="border-left: 4px solid var(--teal);">
        <h3 style="margin-top: 0; font-size: 1rem;">Mindfulness-Based Stress Reduction (MBSR)</h3>
        <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 0.9rem;">8-week program combining meditation, body scanning,
        and gentle yoga. Reduces pain catastrophizing and improves function. Particularly helpful
        as an adjunct — it teaches the skill of observing pain without fear, which is essential
        for all neuroplastic recovery approaches.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="card" style="border-left: 4px solid var(--teal);">
        <h3 style="margin-top: 0; font-size: 1rem;">Acceptance and Commitment Therapy (ACT)</h3>
        <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 0.9rem;">Helps patients accept pain sensations while
        committing to valued actions. Reduces the struggle against pain (which amplifies it) while
        rebuilding a meaningful life. Good evidence for chronic pain, especially as a foundation
        for other techniques.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="card" style="border-left: 4px solid var(--teal);">
        <h3 style="margin-top: 0; font-size: 1rem;">Intensive Short-Term Dynamic Psychotherapy (ISTDP)</h3>
        <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 0.9rem;">A focused psychodynamic approach that targets
        the emotional avoidance patterns driving physical symptoms. A meta-analysis (Abbass et al.)
        found significant effects for somatic disorders. Requires a trained therapist.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h2>What the evidence says</h2>

    <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(200px, 1fr)); gap: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
      <div class="card" style="text-align: center; padding: 1.5rem;">
        <div style="font-size: 2rem; font-weight: 700; color: var(--teal);">66%</div>
        <p style="margin: 0.3rem 0 0; font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--text-muted);">Pain-free after 4 weeks of PRT (JAMA 2021)</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card" style="text-align: center; padding: 1.5rem;">
        <div style="font-size: 2rem; font-weight: 700; color: var(--teal);">98%</div>
        <p style="margin: 0.3rem 0 0; font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--text-muted);">Improved after PRT treatment (JAMA 2021)</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card" style="text-align: center; padding: 1.5rem;">
        <div style="font-size: 2rem; font-weight: 700; color: var(--teal);">5 yr</div>
        <p style="margin: 0.3rem 0 0; font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--text-muted);">PRT results maintained at 5-year follow-up</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card" style="text-align: center; padding: 1.5rem;">
        <div style="font-size: 2rem; font-weight: 700; color: var(--teal);">3-4 wk</div>
        <p style="margin: 0.3rem 0 0; font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--text-muted);">Typical timeframe for results (Schubiner program)</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h2>What tends not to work</h2>
    <p>
      Treatments that target only the body — without addressing the brain-based mechanism — often
      fail for neuroplastic pain:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Opioids and pain medications</strong> — may provide temporary relief but don't
      address the learned neural pathway. Long-term use can worsen central sensitization
      (opioid-induced hyperalgesia).</li>
      <li><strong>Surgery</strong> — studies show back surgery outcomes are no better than
      conservative care for chronic pain without clear nerve compression. Surgery can create
      new pain and reinforce the brain's danger signal.</li>
      <li><strong>Injections</strong> — epidural steroid injections for back pain show no
      long-term benefit over placebo in systematic reviews. They target tissue when the
      problem is neural.</li>
      <li><strong>Passive physical therapy</strong> — massage, ultrasound, TENS — can provide
      temporary comfort but don't retrain the brain. Active approaches (gradual movement,
      desensitization) are more effective.</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="card" style="background: #FFF7ED; border-color: #FDBA74; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
      <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 0.95rem;">
        <strong>Disclaimer:</strong> This is educational information, not medical advice. Always
        work with a qualified healthcare professional. The best outcomes come from an integrative
        approach: medical evaluation to rule out structural causes, coupled with brain-based
        treatment for the neuroplastic component. Many people benefit from combining multiple
        approaches — PRT plus emotional work, for instance.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div style="margin-top: 2rem; display: flex; gap: 1rem; flex-wrap: wrap;">
      <a href="/protocols/prt" class="btn btn-primary">PRT Protocol →</a>
      <a href="/protocols/schubiner" class="btn btn-outline">Schubiner's Method</a>
      <a href="/resources" class="btn btn-outline">All Resources</a>
    </div>
  </article>
</Base>
